english:
  title: Preface to the Farewell of Daoist Xu on His Return Journey
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the third year of the Hongwu era's first reign-title, in the fourth month, a Daoist from the Chaotian Palace who bore the name Yuyan arrived at the royal capital after crossing the sea from Nanjing, bearing incense, silks, and ritual proclamations. He was received in the fields and lodged with all the customary courtesies and reverence. The Ministry of Rites was commanded to provide for the sacrificial rites, and the Court Administrator Li Sungnim was appointed to oversee the proceedings—in which I too took part.

    On the day of ding-you in the fifth month, the assembled officials, bearing ritual tablets, made a joint offering to the spirits of mountains and waters at the southern city. The next day, Yuyan was greatly pleased and eager to return to report his mission. He waited for favorable winds at the harbor of Yeseong.

    Before long, the king said: "When the Daoist arrived, I was somewhat indisposed and unable to perform the proper ceremonies. This weighs upon my heart." He summoned Yuyan back and inquired after his wellbeing, conversing with him at length. Having become well acquainted with my face through the sacrificial proceedings, and observing that I wore the Confucian cap, Yuyan eagerly requested poems. He unpacked his belongings and showed me poems from the masters of the Great Storehouse. I read through them all to the end. Yuyan is truly one who loves poetry. Otherwise, how could such treasures be so readily obtained from a person?

    Thereupon I collected poems from friends and wrote this brief preface to them:

    The lineage of the Daoists, as recorded in Sima Qian's histories, shows how Laozi, serving as keeper of the archives at the Zhou court, was unfulfilled. He composed five thousand words, and through two generations came Gai Gong, whom Cao Can recommended to Emperor Wen, bringing about an age in the Han when punishments were unused. Though we Confucians too serve the realm, our achievements are not necessarily so beautifully accomplished.

    As for what they call bestowing registers, making obeisance to celestial chapters, talismans and incantations, and the elixir of immortality—though each has its explanations, these are convoluted and fanciful, not the true teachings of Laozi. Therefore, those who are his disciples should earnest endeavor to embody their master's way.

    Now our sovereign's brightness rivals the sun and moon. He perceives that in human hearts there is both truth and falsehood, in learning both orthodoxy and heterodoxy. His illumination is complete and without blind spots. In regard to the mystical teachings, he deeply accords with the way of purity and emptiness, hoping thereby to bring the realm to unified peace. His grand design and far-reaching vision surpass the Han dynasty a thousandfold. That Yuyan, having departed from the Chaotian Palace, serves as chief sacrificer for a foreign land ten thousand li distant—this itself reveals his worthiness.

    Observing him, I see his spirit complete and his resolve steadfast, his words concise yet their meaning luminous. In what preserves him, nothing is careless. Through fasting and ablution, he sanctifies his virtue. In performing the sacrifices that must be performed, he establishes the foundation of human governance. Only one who embodies the utmost purity and refinement could partake in such work. This is why Yuyan undertakes this mission.

    That worth is recognized without fixed boundaries also shows how the great court employs its people. Should another like Gai Gong emerge, surely our people would receive such blessings. Yuyan's family name is Xu, his given name is Shihao, and he is from Yangzhou. I record this in full because the actual practice of distant sacrificial rites begins from this time.
  footnotes:
    - 'Gai Gong (蓋公): A legendary Daoist sage whose political influence through Cao Can made the early Han dynasty so stable that punishments became unnecessary. Lee uses this exemplary figure to elevate Yuyan''s mission.'
    - The 'Confucian cap' (儒冠) worn by Lee Saek is a subtle detail suggesting the harmony between Confucian and Daoist values at the Joseon court.
    - The 'Great Storehouse' (大倉) likely refers to a significant collection of classical Chinese philosophical texts.
